delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/title
left and not right: Used for formal title of an artifact (but not individual elements such as classes or properties).
right and not left: This annotation is typically used to describe an artifact such as a controlled vocabulary, document, ontology, or other similar resource.
formal name given to the resource (artifact, such as a controlled vocabulary or ontology)

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/source
left and not right: related resource from which the described resource is derived

The intent is to provide a user with a reference as to how the thing being annotated was derived or arrived at. 
 - The source can be a URL to a standard, common dictionary (e.g. Oxford), or similar reference. Or it can be a short description of where the entity being annotated was derived from.
 - The 'Source' annotation would most likely be used as an annotation on an annotation. For instance annotating a Natural Language definition annotation.
right and not left: related resource from which the described resource is derived

The intent is to provide a user with a reference as to how the thing being annotated was derived or arrived at. The source can be a URL to a standard, common dictionary (e.g., Collins, Merriam-Webster, Oxford), a formal reference such as an ISO standard, or similar reference. Or it can be a short description of a source from which the entity being annotated was derived.

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/publisher
left and not right: Used to document the primary agent (organization or person) responsible for the resource. This will be "Industrial Ontology Foundry" for IOF artifacts.
entity responsible for making the resource available
right and not left: This annotation is typically used to describe an artifact such as a controlled vocabulary, ontology, or other similar resource.
primary party responsible for making the resource available

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/contributor
left and not right: entity responsible for making contributions to the resource
right and not left: party that has made contributions to the resource

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/references
left and not right: related resource that is referenced, cited, or otherwise pointed to by the described resource
right and not left: indicates a related resource that is referenced, cited, or otherwise pointed to by the described resource

delta.subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#changeNote
left and not right: note about a modification to a concept
right and not left: note describing a modification to a resource

delta.subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel
left and not right: alternative lexical label for a resource
right and not left: alternative lexical tag for a resource

delta.subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote
left and not right: note that helps to clarify the meaning and/or the use of a concept
Use of this annotation is optional, but recommended if it will help a user understand the scope and/or context for usage of the concept.
right and not left: note that helps to clarify the meaning of something within the context of the intended use of the resource

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/creator
left and not right: entity responsible for making the resource

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/abstract
left and not right: This annotation is used to describe an artifact such as a vocabulary, ontology, or ontology module.
right and not left: This annotation is typically used to describe an artifact such as a controlled vocabulary, ontology, or other similar resource.

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/license
left and not right: legal document giving official permission to do something with the resource
right and not left: This annotation is typically used to describe an artifact such as a controlled vocabulary, ontology, or other similar resource.
legal document giving official permission to do something with the resource

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/issued
left and not right: date of formal issuance of the resource
This annotation is used to describe an artifact such as a vocabulary, ontology, or ontology module.
right and not left: This annotation is typically used to describe an artifact such as a controlled vocabulary, ontology, or other similar resource.
date of formal issuance of the resource

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/description
left and not right: This annotation is used to describe an artifact such as a vocabulary, ontology, or ontology module.

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/rights
left and not right: information about rights held in and over the resource
right and not left: This annotation is typically used to describe an artifact such as a controlled vocabulary, ontology, or other similar resource.
provides nformation about rights held in and over the resource

delta.subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#example
left and not right: example of the use of a concept

Use of this annotation is optional, but recommended if it will help a user understand the intended interpretation(s).
- This annotation should use at most twice with/on a notion.
- Additional examples or more elaborate examples should be placed in the External Documentation (using rdfs:seeAlso).
right and not left: illustration of the use of some resource

delta.subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#editorialNote
left and not right: note for an editor, translator, or maintainer of the vocabulary
right and not left: note for an editor, translator, or maintainer of the controlled vocabulary or ontology

delta.subject: http://purl.org/dc/terms/modified
left and not right: date on which the resource was changed
right and not left: date on which the resource was most recently revised

delta.subject: http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#definition
left and not right: statement or formal explanation of the meaning of a concept
right and not left: formal statement of the meaning of a resource
